column1: 191050;instagram;2019-01-25 01:58:39;TRUE;;"this past weekend my roommate and i made some signs and marched for justice
repost of caption from my personal page:
this is a lot and and it‚Äôs pretty personal so if you read it - thank you.

i want to start by saying that not all men are actively creating this current harmful and degrading culture for women. i have many wonderful men in my life. and the #metoo movement and feminism need men to speak with us
column2: because we are far more powerful together.

column1: i want to share a few reasons why i march in support of #metoo and women‚Äôs rights:

1. i was assaulted while in college - i was not wearing a short skirt nor was i drunk - and this gives me a chance to publicly say #metoo and join the millions of voices around the world in solidarity so that the next nassar can‚Äôt leave a wake of unbelieved victims.
2. a history of injustice and a trajectory of the same globally for women in court rooms
column3: humans being trafficked - people should be protected and treated with full respect regardless of gender

column1: 3. we are not that far removed from illegal birth control for single women or men-only universities - and are not removed at all from people like nassar and weinstein using their influence and power to manipulate and hurt so many women

4. our country has elected a man as president - to the highest office of power and honor - who publicly admits (and brags) to having violated women as a result of his status. calling attention and paying attention is crucial.
there are so many reasons and these are just a few
column2: but it truly is empowering to join the voices of friends and strangers alike to speak up for all people.

column1: anita hill and christine blasey ford - 20 years apart
column2: with the same familiar story. both sets of male dominated courts did not hear them. but we did. the same conclusion now does not mean the same old story. they were not believed. and yet the wake that they both created has changed so much. and they are reasons why we march - to continue raising awareness on the change that is still needed.

if you find yourself looking for me - you won‚Äôt have to wander dear
for i‚Äôll be resting in the atmosphere - and watching from afar
across the sky just like a shooting star
as you find your future with the one who holds your heart
and i will be so unbelievably happy to see

because you my dear - are one in a million

column1: 191196;instagram;2019-01-25 06:01:54;FALSE;"11 years i've spent looking over my shoulder wondering if i'll hear your voice in a crowd & freeze or fight like ive regretted for years not doing that night.

i release this hurt. i release this anger & rage. i release this hate & i forgive you.
i dont know why things happen & ill never understand what drives a person to hurt or violate them but its no longer mine to understand.
i release you and all haunting thoughts of that night.

column1: 191245;instagram;2019-01-25 08:06:10;FALSE;"how are you going to save yourself by jm holmes is a short story collection that reads like a novel. these interconnected stories follow a decade in the life of four black men from pawtucket
column3: the star of the show who narrates 7 of the 9 stories
column9: the former football star who never quite made it out.

column1: holmes having a book out is a win for african-american literature. constant use of aave/slang without explanation was something i loved (he mentioned ""middies."" i've literally never seen ""mids/reggie/etc"" mentioned in ""highbrow"" literature). holmes had great strength in showing vs telling during high pressure scenes. this strength stood out to me in the story toll for passengers
column2: where gio's cousins are in town & they end up sticking up these rich college kids who crash into his cousin's isaac's car.

column1: holmes is a bold writer. particularly for two stories. the opener
column2: what's wrong with you? what's wrong with me? & be good to me
column3: the third story in the collection. wwwy
column4: wwwm is bold because of how honest he was in tackling the fetishization that can exist in interracial relationships. the closing scene will surely disturb you! he is bold again for how complicit he makes the reader in be good to me. three of the protagonists commit an act of sexual violence & he asks the reader to continue following these men for 6 more stories. this is a demanding request
column5: especially with society's appropriately heightened sensitivity & awareness to sexual violence in the #metoo era. to complete this book is to truly embrace/follow along with some severely flawed men & it is a potential test to see how far you can stretch your empathy.

column1: i recommend this book with hesitations. be good to me = a difficult story. proceed with caution reading that
column2: especially if you have been a victim of sexual violence. i also feel that holmes could have done better w/ his portrayal of black american women. a ""crooked weave"" remark in outside tacoma is one of a few examples of this critique.

column1: holmes next project = a dystopian novel. i look forward to seeing how his undeniable talents translate to the specualtive realm.";;en;#MeToo;;;;;0;;reggiereads;The Villain;;0;False;57;0;0;545;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/3a20abcf58ebfe9d7bf58b7d1e4c3842/5D12D7DD/t51.2885-15/e35/50095680_364081951072103_5349111716433228722_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"how are you going to save yourself by jm holmes is a short story collection that reads like a novel. these interconnected stories follow a decade in the life of four black men from pawtucket

column4: wwwm is bold because of how honest he was in tackling the fetishization that can exist in interracial relationships. the closing scene will surely disturb you! he is bold again for how complicit he makes the reader in be good to me. three of the protagonists commit an act of sexual violence & he asks the reader to continue following these men for 6 more stories. this is a demanding request
column5: especially with society's appropriately heightened sensitivity & awareness to sexual violence in the #metoo era. to complete this book is to truly embrace/follow along with some severely flawed men & it is a potential test to see how far you can stretch your empathy.

column1: 191435;instagram;2019-01-25 14:01:49;FALSE;"hey guys! can we just be real for a moment? i don't often step out and allow myself to be vulnerable with people
column2: but i really feel strongly about this one
column3: so listen up! not all of you know my story
column4: some of you have seen my #metoo post. some may have seen my sister talk on fb lives about being #1in4. it's not something i wear on my sleeve. however
column5: i have to share something.  a lot of you who know my sister know she works for younique and if you've followed her you have heard her talk about the haven retreat. it is a completely free retreat for women over 18 who have lived through childhood sexual abuse. it is a safe haven where they can be educated
column6: empowered and begin (or continue) their healing journey.

column1: i just finished the retreat. i don't tell you this because i want a pat on the back or an 'attagirl or a ""oh i'm so sorry""
column2: i tell you this because i just spent four days having my mind blown. i have had classes and experiences that have left me with a sense of hope i didn't know i could have. the goal at haven retreat is to facilitate healing through education (my mind was blown guys
column3: they explained things in ways i've never experienced before)
column4: experience (the activities have impacted my life in so many ways i won't ever be the same person thanks to so many amazing
column5: empowering experiences) and community (the power of being with a group of women who just ""get"" it
column6: without needing to know details). if you or anyone you know has ever gone through the trauma of childhood sexual abuse can i encourage you to check out haven retreat? it's free to apply
column7: there are no obligations. i am not a younique presenter.. i am in no way affiliated with them.. this is a free retreat and i think every woman who has experienced that kind of trauma deserves to know that she is enough; deserves to have people come up beside her and walk with her through a journey of healing.  i'm including a link.. i encourage you
column8: check it out. i am so grateful to have had the opportunity to attend and make the connections i did and experience all that haven had to offer.

column1: 191526;instagram;2019-01-25 15:34:29;FALSE;"domestic violence laws in california do not protect step parents help make strangulation a felony!

a 12 yr old can figure it out and did text her therapist before we got to her.  imagine how loud you would be screaming if someone 70% larger than you violently grabbed you by the neck and bashed you skull.
when i was finally able to get to my daughter who was four at the time she said ‚Äúmomma did you hear that lady screaming?!‚Äù i said yes i did it was our neighbor she stepped on a nail.
my step daughter immediately gave me this look like you are so lying. my stepdaughter texted her therapist asking what she should do because she was so scared.

so sadly despite or very best efforts to protect her from what her mother did we cannot undo what she was exposed to. we later found out from her that she came out to the balcony and heard the whole thing.

as far as us preventing the mother from seeing her daughter. lie. the daughter was scared out of her pants and upset requesting no contact. this was stated to the family court mediation services and taken into account when emergency temporary custody orders changed. the court and aurelia‚Äôs actions prevented her from seeing her daughter not us.
we then worked with the court to get reunification therapy going to help them repair their already fragile relationship.
the reality today is we have seen my stepdaughter in 13 months. we get no support
column3: no help from the mother and now she wants no relationship with us. what does mom say? she‚Äôs 16 now she can choose. so sad.

column1: there were seasons of seeing each other every day and feeling hope rising.
there were seasons of silence. painful silence.

column2: they didn‚Äôt bring about the lasting miracle that we were looking for.

column1: 191704;instagram;2019-01-25 18:13:36;FALSE;i‚Äôm 36 & today is my 36th day in sobriety. ‚Äúit‚Äôs okay to not be okay.‚Äù inspiration from @recipesforselflove üíúüíúüíú. yesterday was really hard for me. without going into details-as it‚Äôs triggering for me to even talk about-i received a message from someone that brought a very buried memory back to the surface
column2: something i had clearly numbed into distant memory. i skipped dinner & dove into a netflix binge to distract myself
column3: feeling like i couldn‚Äôt handle even thinking about things at the risk of relapse. but these things are bound to come up in early recovery i realized
column4: and each time they do it‚Äôs a sign of something i need to heal. i have been really focusing  on positive affirmations lately but this is one of those times i have to face a demon of my past in order to heal and move on. my doctor recommended i look into emdr (eye movement desensitization and reprocessing) which is said to be a very effective treatment for ptsd and processing traumatic events. had anyone had experience with this modality in their recovery? i look forward to trying it and will post about the experience when i do. #earlysobriety #emdr #emdrtherapy #ptsd #recovery #metoo #unconventionalrecovery;;en;#earlysobriety

column1: road tripped with my home girl so we could learn alllllll about the early warning signs of teens using drugs. ‚Å£

definitely one of the best trainings i‚Äôve ever been to. pretty much ready to deliver a live webinar to all my friends with kids on how to attack the early signs of drug use in teens before it‚Äôs diagnosed the disease of addiction. ‚Å£
we can‚Äôt stop every case but as a parent of three ladies in their 20‚Äôs and 2 boys crawling through the teen years i can tell you it‚Äôs so important to be aware. ‚Å£

drug use isn‚Äôt about good kids versus bad kids. it‚Äôs not about good parents versus bad parents. it‚Äôs the alignment of all the right things at exactly the right time and can absolutely be reduced with education
kids are much smarter than we give them credit for. don‚Äôt assume they haven‚Äôt been exposed. know their friends
column3: routines and cell phone code. set the expectation and boundaries.  follow through with consequences for breaking those boundaries. ‚Å£

column1: and don‚Äôt forget that our teens can have very candid conversations with us. include them in getting the conversation started and simply ask your teen: do you know anyone who uses drugs? what‚Äôs that like for you? ‚Å£
and then listen to their answer from a conversational non judge mental space no matter what they say. ‚Å£
the us makes up 5% of the worlds population. yet we consume 89% of the worlds oxycodone and 99% of the worlds hydrocodone. ‚Å£

column1: 191783;instagram;2019-01-25 19:43:32;FALSE;"watching #survivingrkelly has triggered a lot of folks. having lots of memories. putting this out there for anyone who needs to know they aren't crazy.  the person who took this picture was a pedophile in our seattle scene who targeted young girls. he did this to a bunch of people. he was cool and funny
column2: provided a place for us outcast and punk rock youth and everyone loved him. he invited me in for modeling after grooming me for months and gaining my confidence. we used to talk about everything at his store and i really felt like i had a true friend. he made me feel special. then he made his moves when i least expected it
column3: and told me that 'i' had made him feel this way. i felt trapped and he played on that. i wasn't forced or hurt in a physical way. but he fucked me up. he fucked me up good. he made me feel special
column5: like a piece of meat. he instilled a distrust of men in me
column6: a sense that any kind of physical intimacy involves me being used--that i'm not sure i will ever fully be able to undo.  no one ever talked about this openly in our scene
column7: although we whispered to each other about it. he was never held accountable. when i found out i wasn't the only one
column9: and powerless. i had been taught that if men abused me
column10: it was my fault for letting them do it. so i told no one. i just kept drinking 40s and breaking bottles
column11: doing lines at clubs at 3am. i felt so dirty. but as i had been approached by pedophiles on the street since i was 10
column13: touched and tongue kissed by a drunken uncle in my bed when i was 7
column14: i guess i was already conditioned to not know how to deal with this and protect myself. one thing i will say about the dude that took this picture: he was a sneaky fucker
column15: and he was married. i see the look on my face. i'm uncomfortable. i'm trying to preserve my innocence by looking down. i remember he kept wanting me to look at him and i didnt want to. once he got my gaze
column16: that was how he started his control. i was 16. he was 35. it's taken me a long time to tell this story. to post this photo and tell the truth. i'll be 49 this year.

column1: 191951;instagram;2019-01-25 23:45:03;FALSE;"aviation: how are bridges built? (4/10) by nicholas jones
when i was younger - my mom always told me
that her father built bridges with his bare hands
so i always wondered how he actually built them
and how one man could harbor so much precision under pressure
and so much foresight without fear of the future
as it is with most inquiries into what could have been - or what should have been
i have a few questions that i would have liked to have asked - but i never got the chance
and it‚Äôs these questions that i ask myself everyday - without a single answer to speak of
these questions i could never fully recover from - regardless of how much i‚Äôve tried
so if i could see my old best friend
after seven long years since her last day here
i would ask her where she‚Äôs been - and why she left the way she did
then i would ask how many kids she would have had
if she had found her way here - because i never thought
that it was important enough to ask her
before i knew i‚Äôd never see her again
and if my father was still alive - there would be so many questions i‚Äôd have to ask
like how did he know when he first loved my mother
and how do i distinguish between loving someone for who they really are
and the person that i so desperately want them to be
how can i separate reality from the fantasies in my mind
when hard times are abundant - and the world is just too cold to bear
still - in the hours of nights long passed
i sit right next to rivers red and blue - then i lift my head
and i continue to this day to ask myself
how are bridges built - and how can i build them without you? -
